HEADWORD: Zeugma
<hw>Zeug"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., from Gr. <?/, fr.
<?/ to yoke, join. See <er>Yoke</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A
figure by which an adjective or verb, which agrees with a nearer word,
is, by way of supplement, referred also to another more remote; <as>as,
⟦ldquo⟧hic illius <ex>arma</ex>, hic <ex>currus fuit</ex>;⟦rdquo⟧ where
<ex>fuit</ex>, which agrees directly with <ex>currus</ex>, is referred
also to <ex>arma</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Zeugmatic</ent>⟦br⟧
